#compdef avml
# ============================================================================
# avml - Acquire Volatile Memory for Linux (forensics
#         memory dumper) (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : Microsoft Corporation
# Upstream: https://github.com/microsoft/avml
# crates : avml (binary: avml)
#
# `avml` is Microsoft's portable volatile-memory
# acquisition tool for Linux - the Linux equivalent of
# Windows's WinPMem / x86 LiME alternative. The tool
# captures the contents of physical RAM from a running
# Linux system + writes the snapshot to disk as either
# a raw flat file or a Snappy-compressed structured
# AVML file. The output is consumable by mainstream
# memory forensics frameworks (Volatility, Rekall) for
# post-incident analysis.
#
# avml's design priorities reflect its forensics
# use case:
#   - SINGLE STATIC BINARY: no glibc / libc / OpenSSL
#     dependencies; can be dropped onto an unknown
#     incident-response target without library
#     concerns
#   - MULTIPLE SOURCES: reads from `/dev/crash`,
#     `/proc/kcore`, `/dev/mem`, or a per-distribution
#     module like `/proc/kallsyms` - tries them in
#     order of preference + falls back gracefully
#   - OPTIONAL CLOUD UPLOAD: built-in HTTP PUT + Azure
#     Blob Storage upload via SAS URLs for incident-
#     response over remote-shell access where on-disk
#     storage is unsafe
#   - SNAPPY COMPRESSION: optional compression to keep
#     the captured RAM snapshot under the available
#     local disk space
#
# Usage:
#   avml [OPTIONS] <filename>
#
# Flags (clap derive Parser):
#       --compress             - Snappy-compress the
#                                 output (default off
#                                 = raw flat file)
#       --source <source>      - explicit input source
#                                 (proc-kcore /
#                                 dev-crash /
#                                 dev-mem / ...)
#       --max-disk-usage <MB>  - cap total disk used
#                                 by the output
#                                 (megabytes)
#       --max-disk-usage-percentage <pct>
#                              - cap as percentage of
#                                 free disk space
#                                 (0.01 to 100.0)
#
# Cloud upload (when built with `put` / `blobstore`
# features):
#       --url <url>            - HTTP PUT upload
#                                 destination
#       --sas-url <url>        - Azure Blob SAS URL
#       --sas-block-size <MiB> - per-block size
#                                 (positive integer)
#       --sas-block-concurrency <n>
#                              - upload concurrency
#                                 (positive integer)
#       --delete               - delete local file
#                                 after successful
#                                 upload
#
# Positional:
#   <filename>                 - output file path
#
# The Snappy lane is built on `snap = "1.1"` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep,
# used to compress the captured RAM snapshot when
# `--compress` is set), the canonical Rust Snappy
# library by Andrew Gallant (BurntSushi) - github.com/
# BurntSushi/rust-snappy, 600+ stars.
#
# The `snap` crate is a *line-by-line safe-Rust port*
# of Google's reference Snappy C++ library, done by
# BurntSushi (the same author as ripgrep, the Rust
# regex crate, BurntSushi/toml at Axis 243, fst, and
# xsv). Gallant's port preserves byte-identical output
# vs Google's reference encoder + supports both the
# `snappy raw block` and `snappy framed` wire formats.
#
# This makes BurntSushi/rust-snappy the de-facto Rust
# Snappy implementation + reinforces Gallant's
# position as the canonical Rust author for several
# spec-bound axes:
#   - Axis 222 (XXHash): BurntSushi's ucd-generate-
#     derived XXHash crate
#   - Axis 243 (TOML): BurntSushi/toml-test + the Go
#     library
#   - Axis 253 (Snappy, THIS AXIS): BurntSushi/rust-
#     snappy
#
# Gallant's canonical-library footprint across the
# Rust ecosystem (regex / ripgrep / fst / xsv /
# rust-snappy / toml-test) is unusually large for a
# single author - it's the Rust equivalent of Daniel
# Lemire's cross-language root-of-trust position at
# Roaring Bitmap (Axis 250).
#
# avml uses `snap::write::FrameEncoder` to wrap the
# output file in a Snappy-framed compression stream,
# producing the AVML on-disk format's compressed
# variant. Snappy was chosen over heavier compression
# algorithms (LZ4 was at Axis 223, zstd is a likely
# future axis) because of its very-fast decompression
# path - Volatility + Rekall need to scan the captured
# memory at full speed during the analysis pass, so
# decompression overhead is the dominant cost.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 253 :: Snappy compression (Google fast LZ77
#              variant, optimized for decompression
#              throughput)
# Round 1457 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 253
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : BurntSushi/rust-snappy      - Andrew
#                                          Gallant's
#                                          line-by-line
#                                          safe-Rust port
#                                          of Google's
#                                          reference C++
#                                          Snappy library;
#                                          de-facto Rust
#                                          canonical
#   Go      : golang/snappy               - Go core
#                                          team's
#                                          maintained
#                                          port in the
#                                          golang/snappy
#                                          repo;
#                                          (originally
#                                          part of
#                                          golang/leveldb,
#                                          extracted in
#                                          2016)
#   TS/Node : @node-rs/snappy             - napi-rs
#                                          binding to
#                                          BurntSushi/
#                                          rust-snappy;
#                                          inherits
#                                          Gallant's
#                                          Rust impl
#                                          via N-API
#
# Snappy is a clean spec-bound axis - Google's
# `snappy-format-description.txt` defines the
# block + framed wire formats byte-for-byte.
# Compliant implementations produce byte-identical
# output for the same input + cross-decode correctly.
# The test corpus from Google's Snappy repo is the
# canonical reference; all three lanes pass it.
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - BurntSushi/rust-snappy (Rust): line-by-line
#     port of Google's reference C++ source;
#     preserves byte-for-byte output equivalence;
#     part of Andrew Gallant's broader canonical-
#     Rust-library footprint (regex / ripgrep / fst /
#     xsv / toml-test)
#   - golang/snappy (Go): originally part of
#     golang/leveldb (the Go LevelDB port), extracted
#     into its own `golang/snappy` repo in 2016 +
#     maintained by the Go core team since
#   - @node-rs/snappy (Node): napi-rs binding to
#     BurntSushi/rust-snappy - the Node slot binds to
#     the same Rust implementation that powers the
#     Rust slot, completing the Rust-roots cycle
#
# The Node-binds-to-Rust pattern at the Snappy slot
# is structurally identical to @node-rs/argon2 (Axis
# 244 binds to RustCrypto argon2) and @chainsafe/
# libp2p-quic (Axis 249 binds to quinn-rs). The
# napi-rs binding shape is increasingly the Node
# ecosystem's preferred way to get high-performance
# spec-bound primitives without reimplementing them
# in JS.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level -
# Snappy bitstream produced by BurntSushi/rust-snappy
# + golang/snappy + @node-rs/snappy decompresses
# byte-identically through any of the others. Google's
# test corpus validates this cross-library byte-
# equivalence.
#
# Axis 253 opens with the Rust slot at Andrew Gallant's
# canonical safe-Rust port.
# ============================================================================

_avml() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--compress[Snappy-compress the output]' \
        '--source[explicit input source]:source:(proc-kcore dev-crash dev-mem)' \
        '--max-disk-usage[cap disk usage in MB]:MB:' \
        '--max-disk-usage-percentage[cap as percentage of free disk (0.01-100.0)]:pct:' \
        '--url[HTTP PUT upload destination]:url:' \
        '--sas-url[Azure Blob SAS URL]:url:' \
        '--sas-block-size[per-block upload size (MiB)]:MiB:' \
        '--sas-block-concurrency[upload concurrency]:n:' \
        '--delete[delete local file after successful upload]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1:output file:_files'
}

_avml "$@"
